French Division 1|1997\u201398]], 1999\u20132000<ref name=magliarossonera.it/><ref name=\"gq\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gqitalia.it/sport/calcio/2018/07/09/calciomercato-i-10-migliori-calciatori-italiani-in-francia |title=Calciomercato, i 10 migliori calciatori italiani in Francia |publisher=GQ Italia |language=Italian |last1=Stabile |first1=Adriano |date=9 July 2018 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"francefootball\">{{cite web |url=https://www.francefootball.fr/fiche/joueur/simone-marco-ita/2943 |title=Marco Simone |publisher=France Football |language=French |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref>\n*A.C. Milan Hall of Fame<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Marco Simone\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Lequipe|2943}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Simone_Marco}}\n*[http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=27&squadra=2 Profile at FIGC.it] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ra\u00ed]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] captain|years=1998\u20131999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[\u00c9ric Rab\u00e9sandratana ]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Ligue 1 Player of the Year}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Marco Simone managerial positions\n|list =\n{{Ratchaburi Mitr Phol F.C. managers}}\n{{AS Monaco FC managers}}\n{{FC Lausanne-Sport managers}}\n{{Tours FC managers}}\n{{Stade Lavallois managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simone, Marco}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Como 1907 players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Legnano players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Paris Saint-Germain F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Monaco]]\n[[Category:AS Monaco FC players]]\n[[Category:OGC Nice players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Italian football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Varese]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Virtus Bergamo Alzano Seriate 1909 players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:AS Monaco FC managers]]\n[[Category:FC Lausanne-Sport managers]]\n[[Category:Tours FC managers]]\n[[Category:Stade Lavallois managers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Italy B international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Marco Simone\n| image       = Marco Simone (5038454279).jpg\n| fullname    = Marco Simone\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|1|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Castellanza]], Italy\n| height      = 1.70 m\n| currentclub = \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]], [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1986\u20131989\n| years2 = 1987\u20131988\n| years3 = 1989\u20131997\n| years4 = 1997\u20131999\n| years5 = 1999\u20132001\n| years6 = 2001\u20132002\n| years7 = 2002\u20132003\n| years8 = 2004\n| years9 = 2005\u20132006\n| clubs1 = [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[A.S.D. F.C. Alzano|Virescit]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n| clubs4 = [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]\n| clubs5 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| clubs6 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n| clubs7 = [[AS Monaco|Monaco]]\n| clubs8 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| clubs9 = [[A.C. Legnano|Legnano]]\n| caps1 = 36\n| caps2 = 33\n| caps3 = 168\n| caps4 = 59\n| caps5 = 69\n| caps6 = 9\n| caps7 = 5\n| caps8 = 7\n| caps9 = 1\n| totalcaps = 387\n| goals1 = 6\n| goals2 = 15\n| goals3 = 49\n| goals4 = 22\n| goals5 = 28\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalgoals = 120\n| nationalyears1 = 1988\u20131990\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 16\n| nationalgoals1 = 7\n| nationalyears2 = 1992\u20131996\n| nationalteam2 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2011\u20132012\n| managerclubs1 = [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs2 = [[FC Lausanne-Sport|Lausanne-Sport]]\n| manageryears3 = 2015\u20132016\n| managerclubs3 = [[Tours FC|Tours]]\n| manageryears4 = 2016\u20132017\n| manageryears5 = 2017\u20132018<ref>[http://www.goal.com/it/news/7/calciomercato/2017/04/11/34512852/brutte-notizie-per-marco-simone-lex-milan-%C3%A8-stato-esonerato Brutte notizie per Marco Simone: l'ex Milan \u00e8 stato esonerato dal Laval]\u201a goal.com, 11 April 2017</ref>\n| managerclubs4 = [[Stade Lavallois|Laval]]\n| managerclubs5 = [[Club Africain]]\n| manageryears6 = 2019\n| managerclubs6 = [[Ratchaburi Mitr Phol F.C.|Ratchaburi Mitr Phol]]\n|manageryears7  = 2019\n|managerclubs7  = [[SCC Mohamm\u00e9dia]]\n}}\n\n'''Marco Simone''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8marko si\u02c8mo\u02d0ne}}; born 7 January 1969) is an Italian former professional [[association football|football]]er, who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]]. He most prominently played for [[A.C. Milan]], with whom he won four [[Serie A]] championships and two [[UEFA Champions League]] titles, as well as French club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]], and Mon\u00e9gasque outfit [[AS Monaco FC|AS Monaco]]. At international level, Simone played four games for the [[Italy national football team|Italian national team]].\n\nAs a manager, Simone, has also served as the head coach of [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in [[Ligue 2]], and [[FC Lausanne-Sport|Lausanne-Sport]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nSimone was born in [[Castellanza]]. He debuted in [[Serie A]] for [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]] on 11 January 1987. After a few appearances in the top-flight Serie A, he was put [[loan (football)|on loan]] at [[A.S.D. F.C. Alzano|Virescit Boccaleone]] in the secondary [[Serie C1]] league. He scored 15 goals for Virescit in the 1987\u201388 season, and finished as top scorer of the Serie C1 league.<ref name=magliarossonera.it>{{cite web|title=Marco Simone|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/protagonisti/Gioc-Simone.html|publisher=Maglia Rossonera|accessdate=13 May 2015|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to [[Como Calcio 1907|Como]] for the [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389 Serie A season]], in which he scored 6 goals. Como finished dead last in the tournament, and was [[relegated]] to [[Serie B]].\n\n===Milan===\nIn the summer of 1989, Simone was brought into the squad of third-place finishers [[A.C. Milan]] by manager [[Arrigo Sacchi]]. His stay at Milan would be long and successful, as he won the 1990 [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] under manager Sacchi, as well as four Serie A titles in five years from 1992 to 1996 and the 1994 [[UEFA Champions League]] under the management of [[Fabio Capello]].<ref name=magliarossonera.it/><ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Marco Simone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/marco-simone|title=A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Marco Simone|website=acmilan.com|accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis best season for Milan came during the [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395 Serie A season]], where he scored 17 goals in 30 games, as well as 4 in the Champions League, for a total of 21 goals in all competitions, as Milan reached the [[1995 UEFA Champions League Final]], only to be defeated by [[Ajax F.C.|Ajax]]. He also managed 11 goals in all competitions during the [[1995\u201396 A.C. Milan season|1995\u201396 season]], 8 of which came in [[1995\u201396 Serie A|Serie A]], finishing as the club's second highest goalscorer behind [[George Weah]] as Milan won the Serie A title. Despite competing for the attacking spots at Milan with the three [[FIFA World Player of the Year]] award winners [[Marco van Basten]] (1992), [[Roberto Baggio]] (1993) and [[George Weah]] (1995) (as well as the presence of [[Ruud Gullit]], [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107]], [[Daniele Massaro]], [[Paolo Di Canio]], [[Jean-Pierre Papin]], [[Christophe Dugarry]], and [[Brian Laudrup]]), he scored a total of 74 goals in 245 games in all competitions for Milan.<ref name=magliarossonera.it/><ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.acmilandk.net/club/index.php?module=pagesetter&func=viewpub&tid=3&pid=4 Marco Simone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928125702/http://www.acmilandk.net/club/index.php?module=pagesetter&func=viewpub&tid=3&pid=4 |date=28 September 2007 }} at ''ACMilan.dk''</ref>\n\n===International debut===\nDuring his time with Milan, Simone also made his senior debut for the [[Italy national football team|Italian national team]] on 19 December 1992, under then national team manager Arrigo Sacchi, in a 2\u20131 away win in a [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|1994 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Malta national football team|Malta]]. He would go on to play four games in total for the national team between 1992 and 1996, but did not score any goals for Italy.<ref name=magliarossonera.it/><ref name=\"figc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=27&squadra=2|title=Nazionale in cifre: Simone, Marco|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Later career in France, Monaco and return to Italy===\nIn 1997, Simone moved abroad to play for French club [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]], with whom he won both domestic cups in his first season. He scored in both the [[1998 Coupe de la Ligue Final|Coupe de la Ligue]] final and the [[1998 Coupe de France Final|Coupe de France]] final against [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] and [[RC Lens|Lens]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news \n|url=https://archivesparisfootball.wordpress.com/2014/04/13/psg-bordeaux-2-2-4-2-tab-040498-coupe-de-la-ligue-97-98/\n|title=PSG \u2013 Bordeaux 2-2 (4-2 tab), 04/04/98, Coupe de la Ligue 97-98\n|publisher=archivesparisfootball.wordpress.com\n|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n|url=https://archivesparisfootball.wordpress.com/2014/05/03/psg-lens-2-1-020598-coupe-de-france-97-98/\n|title=PSG \u2013 Lens 2-1, 02/05/98, Coupe de France 97-98\n|publisher=archivesparisfootball.wordpress.com\n|accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref> He transferred to [[AS Monaco FC|AS Monaco]] in 1999. He scored 21 goals and made 15 assists in 34 games during the [[1999\u20132000 French Division 1|1999\u20132000 season]], and helped Monaco win the [[Ligue 1]] championship in 2000. He returned to Milan for parts of the [[2001\u201302 Serie A|2001\u201302 Serie A season]], scoring his last goal with the Rossoneri in Coppa Italia against Lazio in 2002. He returned to Monaco, but rarely played during the [[2002\u201303 Ligue 1]] season.<ref name=magliarossonera.it/>\n\nFollowing an unsuccessful [[2003\u201304 Ligue 1|season]] playing for [[OGC Nice]], he retired from football in 2004, at the age of 35. He made a short come-back as he played a single game for [[Serie C2]] club [[A.C. Legnano|Legnano]] in 2005.<ref name=magliarossonera.it/>\n\n==Style of play==\nSimone was a diminutive [[Forward (association football)|forward]], gifted with pace, good movement, an eye for goal, and excellent technique. He was capable of playing in several attacking positions, and was best used as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]], due to his small stature and slender physical build, although he was also capable of playing in a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|central role]] as a main [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], or even as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]].<ref name=magliarossonera.it/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.milannews.it/terza-pagina-milanday/l-uomo-in-piu-36089 |title=L'uomo in pi\u00f9 |publisher=MilanNews.it |language=Italian |date=9 October 2010 |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/68275/simone-appointed-tours |title=Simone appointed at Tours |publisher=Football Italia |date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=21 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[A.C. Milan|Milan]]||[[1989\u201390 Serie A|1989-90]]||rowspan=8|[[Serie A]]||21||1||3||1||5||1||32*<sup>1</sup>||3\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Serie A|1990\u201391]]||14||4||6||2||2||0||22||6\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Serie A|1991\u201392]]||15||7||4||1||0||0||19||8\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Serie A|1992\u201393]]||13||5||4||0||8||4||25||9\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Serie A|1993\u201394]]||25||3||1||0||7||2||34*<sup>2</sup>||6*<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]]||30||17||3||0||9||4||45*<sup>3</sup>||21\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Serie A|1995\u201396]]||27||8||3||1||5||1||35||10\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397]]||23||4||3||2||6||4||33*<sup>4</sup>||10\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!168||49||27||7||42||16||245||73\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|PSG]]||[[1997\u201398 Division 1|1997\u201398]]||rowspan=2|[[Ligue 1|Division 1]]||28||13||3||2||6||4||41*<sup>5</sup>||22*<sup>5</sup>\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Division 1|1998\u201399]]||31||9||1||0||2||1||37*<sup>6</sup>||10\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!59||22||4||2||8||5||78||32\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]||[[1999\u20132000 D